[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 7.4: ED Visit Prediction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium · **Phase:** Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.03 per patient per scoring cycle
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's a frustrating fact about emergency departments in the United States: somewhere between 30% and 70% of ED visits (depending on the study and definition) are for conditions that could have been managed in a primary care or urgent care setting. Not all of them. Not even most of them. But a significant chunk. A patient with poorly controlled diabetes shows up at 2 AM because their blood sugar is at 400 and they ran out of insulin three days ago. A COPD patient who missed their last two pulmonary rehab appointments comes in gasping because their exacerbation wasn't caught early. A kid with recurrent asthma arrives by ambulance because the family didn't have a nebulizer at home and the after-hours clinic was closed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m These visits are expensive (the average ED visit costs 5-10x the equivalent outpatient encounter), disruptive to the patient's life, and often signal a failure of the care delivery system upstream. The ED didn't fail the patient. The system around the patient failed to catch a worsening trajectory before it became a crisis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is where ED visit prediction comes in. The goal is not to predict who will have a car accident or an acute MI. Those are genuinely unpredictable emergencies. The goal is to identify the patients whose utilization pattern, clinical history, medication adherence, and social circumstances make them likely to show up in the ED in the next 30 to 90 days for a condition that, with the right outreach, might have been prevented.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The stakes are real on both sides. If you identify these patients accurately, a care manager can reach out: adjust medications, schedule a same-week appointment, connect them to transportation, set up a home health check. If you identify them inaccurately, you waste scarce care management resources on patients who were never at risk, while the actual high-utilizers slip through.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m And here's the part nobody tells you upfront: the hardest problem isn't building the model. It's building the system that turns a prediction into an action that actually changes the outcome. A perfect score means nothing without an intervention pathway.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: How ED Risk Prediction Works
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Prediction Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At its core, ED visit prediction is a supervised binary classification problem with a time horizon. You're asking: "Will this patient have at least one ED visit within the next N days?" where N is typically 30, 60, or 90 days depending on your intervention capacity and turnaround time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The choice of time horizon matters more than most teams realize at the start. A 30-day window gives you the most actionable predictions (you know the risk is imminent, so outreach feels urgent), but it also gives you the least time to intervene effectively. A 90-day window gives you more time to act, but the predictions are necessarily less precise because you're forecasting further into the future. Most production systems settle on 30 or 60 days, scoring patients weekly or biweekly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The output isn't binary in practice. You don't want "yes/no." You want a calibrated probability: "This patient has a 34% likelihood of an ED visit in the next 60 days." Calibration matters because care managers need to prioritize a list. A patient at 34% and a patient at 78% both need outreach, but in different order and with different urgency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Makes This Different From Other Risk Models
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ED visit prediction sits at an awkward intersection that makes it harder than, say, readmission prediction or no-show prediction:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The outcome is partially preventable.** Not all ED visits can be prevented, and you can't easily label historical data as "preventable" or "non-preventable" after the fact. Your model is trained on all ED visits, but your intervention only matters for the preventable subset. This creates a fundamental ceiling on useful accuracy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The drivers are multi-dimensional.** Clinical factors (disease burden, medication complexity, recent hospitalizations) matter, but so do behavioral factors (appointment adherence, refill patterns) and social factors (transportation access, housing stability, food security). Most healthcare data systems capture the clinical piece well, the behavioral piece partially, and the social piece barely at all.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The base rate is low-ish.** In a general insured population, maybe 5-15% of members will have an ED visit in any given 60-day window. In a high-risk chronic disease panel, it might be 20-30%. Either way, you're dealing with class imbalance, which means naive accuracy metrics are misleading. A model that says "nobody will go to the ED" is 85% accurate and completely useless.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Feature Engineering: What Actually Predicts ED Use
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The literature on ED utilization prediction is fairly mature. Here are the feature families that consistently show up in published models, roughly ordered by predictive importance:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior utilization history.** The single strongest predictor of a future ED visit is having had a prior ED visit. Frequency, recency, and pattern (escalating vs. stable vs. declining) all matter. Patients with 3+ ED visits in the past 12 months are a qualitatively different population than patients with zero.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Chronic disease burden.** Number of active chronic conditions, their severity (HCC scores, Charlson/Elixhauser indices), and their control status (is the diabetes well-managed or poorly-managed based on recent labs). Not just presence of conditions, but trajectory of those conditions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication adherence signals.** Proportion of Days Covered (PDC) for key medications. Gap days between fills. Number of active prescriptions (polypharmacy is a risk factor). Whether the patient has filled their maintenance medications on schedule.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care engagement patterns.** Missed appointments, gaps in preventive care, time since last PCP visit. Patients who are disengaging from routine care are often the ones who show up in the ED because they have nowhere else to go when things get bad.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social determinants (when available).** Homelessness indicators, food insecurity flags, transportation barriers, social isolation, dual-eligible status (Medicare + Medicaid), neighborhood-level deprivation indices. These are powerful predictors but often missing from structured data. Area-level proxies (using census data linked by zip code) partially fill the gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal patterns.** Seasonality (respiratory conditions spike in winter), time since last major clinical event (surgery, hospitalization, diagnosis), and acceleration of utilization (is the patient's visit frequency increasing month over month).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Model Architecture Choices
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Several model families work well for this problem:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gradient-boosted trees (XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost).** The workhorse of healthcare risk prediction. Handle mixed feature types, missing values, and non-linear relationships naturally. Interpretable via SHAP values. Train quickly on tabular data. This is where most production systems land.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Logistic regression.** Simpler, fully interpretable, easier to explain to clinical stakeholders. Works well when features are carefully engineered. Still a reasonable choice when you need maximum transparency or have regulatory requirements for full model explainability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Survival models (Cox proportional hazards, random survival forests).** Better at modeling time-to-event rather than binary classification. If "when will this patient go to the ED?" matters more than "will they?", survival models are worth the added complexity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep learning (LSTM, Transformers on longitudinal claims).** Can learn temporal patterns from raw event sequences without manual feature engineering. More data-hungry, harder to explain, and often only marginally better than well-engineered gradient-boosted models for this task. Worth exploring if you have millions of members and strong engineering talent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For most organizations starting out, gradient-boosted trees with carefully engineered features are the right answer. You get 90% of the achievable performance with 30% of the complexity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Calibration: Why Raw Scores Aren't Enough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A model might output "0.72" for a patient. What does that mean? If the model is well-calibrated, it means that among all patients the model scores at 0.72, approximately 72% actually have an ED visit in the prediction window. Calibration is the property that makes probability estimates trustworthy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most ML models are not naturally well-calibrated. They rank patients correctly (higher-risk patients get higher scores) but the absolute probabilities are often wrong. Platt scaling or isotonic regression applied after model training can fix this. It sounds minor, but care managers need to trust that "high risk" actually means high risk, especially when they're deciding how to spend limited outreach time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Data Aggregation] -> [Feature Engineering] -> [Model Scoring] -> [Risk Stratification] -> [Intervention Routing]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Data Aggregation.** Pull together the raw ingredients: claims history, EHR encounters, pharmacy fills, lab results, demographic data, and (if available) social determinant indicators. This typically means a nightly or weekly ETL pipeline that consolidates data from multiple source systems into a unified patient-level feature store.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature Engineering.** Transform raw events into predictive signals: count ED visits in the past 6 months, calculate medication adherence ratios, compute time since last PCP visit, flag accelerating utilization patterns. This is where domain expertise makes the biggest difference. A data scientist who understands healthcare operations will build better features than one who doesn't, even with the same algorithms.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Model Scoring.** Run the trained model against the current feature set for all active patients. This produces a raw probability estimate for each patient. Scoring typically runs on a batch schedule (weekly or biweekly) rather than real-time, because the features themselves don't change moment-to-moment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Risk Stratification.** Apply calibration, assign patients to risk tiers (high/medium/low), and generate a prioritized outreach list. The stratification thresholds should be set based on your care management capacity: if you can reach out to 200 patients per week, set the "high-risk" threshold so it captures roughly 200 patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Intervention Routing.** Route high-risk patients to the appropriate intervention: care management outreach, pharmacy consultation, social work referral, or automated patient engagement (text reminders, portal messages). The routing logic is often rule-based on top of the risk score, incorporating what the model identified as the primary risk driver for each patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is not a real-time system. The prediction window is 30-90 days. Running weekly batch scoring is appropriate for the tempo of the interventions you're trying to trigger.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and hosting.** SageMaker provides the managed ML infrastructure for the entire model lifecycle: training gradient-boosted models at scale, running hyperparameter tuning jobs, hosting the trained model for batch inference, and managing model versions. For a batch-scoring workload like this, SageMaker Batch Transform is the right deployment pattern (score all patients at once, no need for a real-time endpoint sitting idle between scoring cycles).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Glue for data aggregation and feature engineering.** The ETL pipeline that consolidates claims, pharmacy, lab, and encounter data into patient-level features is a classic Glue workload: scheduled, Spark-based, handling joins across large datasets. Glue also maintains the Data Catalog, which makes the feature store discoverable and auditable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for data lake storage.** Raw source data, engineered features, model artifacts, and scoring results all live in S3. The data lake architecture gives you full lineage: you can always trace a risk score back to the specific features that produced it, and those features back to the specific claims and encounters that generated them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Athena for ad-hoc analysis and monitoring.** Clinicians and analysts need to query risk scores, drill into feature drivers, and validate model outputs. Athena's serverless SQL interface against the S3 data lake makes this accessible without provisioning infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for operational risk scores.** Once batch scoring completes, the active risk scores (current tier, primary risk drivers, recommended interventions) land in DynamoDB for low-latency lookup by the care management workflow tools. When a care manager opens a patient's record, the risk score needs to appear in milliseconds, not minutes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** The weekly scoring pipeline (aggregate data, engineer features, run batch transform, calibrate scores, write to DynamoDB, generate outreach lists) has dependencies between steps and needs error handling at each stage. Step Functions provides the workflow orchestration with built-in retry logic and failure notifications.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring and alerting.** Model drift detection (are the prediction distributions shifting?), pipeline health (did this week's scoring job complete successfully?), and operational SLAs (did the outreach list reach the care management system by Monday morning?).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Data Sources
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         A[Claims Data\nS3 / Data Lake]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         B[EHR Encounters\nS3 / Data Lake]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         C[Pharmacy Fills\nS3 / Data Lake]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         D[Lab Results\nS3 / Data Lake]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         E[SDOH Indicators\nS3 / Data Lake]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Weekly Pipeline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         F[AWS Glue\nFeature Engineering]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         G[S3\nFeature Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         H[SageMaker\nBatch Transform]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         I[Post-Processing\nCalibration + Stratification]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Operational
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         J[DynamoDB\nActive Risk Scores]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         K[Care Management\nOutreach Lists]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L[API Gateway + Lambda\nScore Lookup API]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A --> F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B --> F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C --> F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D --> F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E --> F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F --> G
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G --> H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H --> I
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I --> J
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I --> K
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J --> L
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M[Step Functions\nOrchestration] -.->|coordinates| F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M -.->|coordinates| H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M -.->|coordinates| I
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style G fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style H fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style J fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, AWS Glue, Amazon S3, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Step Functions, Amazon Athena, AWS Lambda, Amazon API Gateway, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTransformJob`, `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `states:StartExecution`, `athena:StartQueryExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: patient claims and clinical data are PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); SageMaker: KMS for training volumes, model artifacts, and batch transform output; Glue: security configuration with KMS; all traffic over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **DynamoDB PITR** | Enable Point-in-Time Recovery for risk score tables; supports audit and incident response |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker and Glue in private subnets with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker API, CloudWatch Logs. No internet egress for PHI-processing components. Enable VPC Flow Logs. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all SageMaker, Glue, S3, and DynamoDB API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | CMS Synthetic Medicare Claims (SynPUF) dataset for development. Never use real patient data in non-production environments. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Glue ETL: ~$5-20/run depending on data volume. SageMaker Batch Transform: ~$2-10/run for 100K patients. DynamoDB: pennies at this write volume. Total weekly pipeline: $10-40 for a 100K member population. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Trains gradient-boosted model; runs weekly batch inference via Batch Transform |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL pipeline: aggregates source data, engineers patient-level features on schedule |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake: raw data, feature store, model artifacts, scoring output |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Operational store: current risk scores for low-latency API lookup |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates weekly pipeline: ETL, scoring, post-processing, delivery |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Athena** | Ad-hoc SQL queries against feature store and scoring results |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | API handler for score lookups; post-processing logic (calibration, routing) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | REST API for care management systems to retrieve patient risk scores |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Pipeline monitoring, drift detection alarms, SLA tracking |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing storage and compute |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-examples`](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): Comprehensive SageMaker examples including batch transform, built-in algorithms (XGBoost), and model monitoring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`aws-healthcare-lifescience-ai-ml`](https://github.com/aws-samples/aws-healthcare-lifescience-ai-ml): Healthcare-specific ML examples on AWS including predictive analytics patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-mlops-workshop`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-sagemaker-mlops-workshop): End-to-end MLOps pipeline patterns with SageMaker, Step Functions, and model registry
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Data aggregation.** The pipeline begins by consolidating patient data from multiple source systems into a unified view. Claims data provides ED visit history and diagnoses. Pharmacy data reveals medication adherence. EHR encounters show care engagement patterns. Lab results indicate disease control. And where available, social determinant indicators flag transportation, housing, or food security barriers. This consolidation runs on a schedule (weekly for most implementations) and produces a patient-level row for every active member. Skip this step and you're building predictions on incomplete information, which in practice means you'll identify the clinically complex patients (who have lots of claims data) while missing the socially complex patients (whose risk drivers live outside the clinical record).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION aggregate_patient_data(scoring_date):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Define the lookback period: how far back we look for historical patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 24 months captures seasonal patterns and gives enough utilization history.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     lookback_start = scoring_date - 24 months
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull claims-based utilization: ED visits, inpatient stays, office visits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Group by patient, so each row summarizes one patient's entire history.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     claims_summary = QUERY claims_table:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SELECT patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                COUNT(ed_visits in last 6 months) as ed_visits_6mo,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                COUNT(ed_visits in last 12 months) as ed_visits_12mo,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                COUNT(inpatient_stays in last 12 months) as ip_stays_12mo,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                COUNT(office_visits in last 6 months) as office_visits_6mo,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                DAYS_SINCE(most_recent_ed_visit) as days_since_last_ed,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                DAYS_SINCE(most_recent_pcp_visit) as days_since_last_pcp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE service_date BETWEEN lookback_start AND scoring_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         GROUP BY patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull pharmacy data: medication adherence and polypharmacy indicators.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     pharmacy_summary = QUERY pharmacy_table:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SELECT patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                COUNT(DISTINCT active_medications) as active_med_count,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                AVG(proportion_days_covered) as avg_pdc,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                MIN(proportion_days_covered) as min_pdc,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                COUNT(gap_days > 7) as med_gap_events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE fill_date BETWEEN lookback_start AND scoring_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         GROUP BY patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pull chronic condition indicators and severity scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     condition_summary = QUERY diagnosis_table:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SELECT patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                COUNT(DISTINCT chronic_condition_categories) as chronic_count,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                MAX(hcc_risk_score) as hcc_score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                HAS_CONDITION('diabetes') as has_diabetes,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                HAS_CONDITION('copd') as has_copd,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                HAS_CONDITION('chf') as has_chf,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                HAS_CONDITION('mental_health') as has_mental_health
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE diagnosis_date BETWEEN lookback_start AND scoring_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         GROUP BY patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Join all summaries into a single patient-level feature table.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // LEFT JOIN ensures we keep all patients even if they're missing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // pharmacy or condition data (which is itself informative).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient_features = JOIN claims_summary, pharmacy_summary, condition_summary
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                        ON patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                        TYPE: LEFT JOIN (keep all patients)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN patient_features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Feature engineering.** Raw counts and dates aren't directly useful for prediction. This step transforms them into signals that capture the patterns most predictive of future ED use. The key insight: it's not just "how many ED visits" but "is the frequency accelerating?" and "what's the gap between routine care and acute care?" Ratio features, trend features, and interaction features often outperform the raw inputs. Skip this step and your model will be mediocre. Invest here and you'll outperform published benchmarks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION engineer_features(patient_features, scoring_date):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     enhanced = patient_features  // start with the raw aggregated data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient in enhanced:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // UTILIZATION TRAJECTORY: Is ED use accelerating?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Compare recent (6mo) to historical (12mo) rate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // A ratio > 1.0 means utilization is increasing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF patient.ed_visits_12mo > 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.ed_acceleration = (patient.ed_visits_6mo * 2) / patient.ed_visits_12mo
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.ed_acceleration = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // CARE ENGAGEMENT GAP: Ratio of acute to routine care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Patients who use the ED frequently but see their PCP rarely
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // are a qualitatively different risk than frequent ED users who
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // also engage with primary care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_visits = patient.ed_visits_6mo + patient.office_visits_6mo
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF total_visits > 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.ed_to_total_ratio = patient.ed_visits_6mo / total_visits
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.ed_to_total_ratio = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // MEDICATION RISK: Combine adherence and complexity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // High medication count + low adherence = strong risk signal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient.med_risk_score = patient.active_med_count * (1 - patient.avg_pdc)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // RECENCY SIGNAL: How recently did they use the ED?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Inverse of days since last visit. Recent visits are much more
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // predictive than visits 18 months ago.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF patient.days_since_last_ed is not NULL:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.ed_recency = 1.0 / (patient.days_since_last_ed + 1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.ed_recency = 0  // never visited ED in lookback window
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // PCP DISENGAGEMENT: Days since last PCP visit, normalized.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Patients who haven't seen their PCP in 6+ months are at higher risk.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient.pcp_disengaged = 1 IF patient.days_since_last_pcp > 180 ELSE 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // DISEASE COMPLEXITY INTERACTION: Multiple chronic conditions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // combined with poor medication adherence is multiplicative risk.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient.complexity_adherence_interaction = patient.chronic_count * (1 - patient.min_pdc)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN enhanced
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Model scoring.** The trained model receives the engineered feature set and produces a raw probability estimate for each patient. In production, this is a batch operation: all active patients are scored in a single pass. The model itself is a gradient-boosted tree (XGBoost) trained on historical data where the label was "had an ED visit within 60 days of the feature extraction date." The output is a probability between 0 and 1. These raw probabilities need calibration before they're operationally useful (next step). Skip calibration and you'll have a model that ranks patients correctly but whose absolute probability estimates are systematically too high or too low.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION score_patients(feature_table, model_artifact):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load the trained model artifact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // In production, this is versioned and tracked in a model registry.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     model = LOAD_MODEL(model_artifact)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Define which columns are model inputs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // These must match exactly what the model was trained on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     feature_columns = [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "ed_visits_6mo", "ed_visits_12mo", "ip_stays_12mo",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "office_visits_6mo", "days_since_last_ed", "days_since_last_pcp",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "active_med_count", "avg_pdc", "min_pdc", "med_gap_events",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "chronic_count", "hcc_score",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "has_diabetes", "has_copd", "has_chf", "has_mental_health",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "ed_acceleration", "ed_to_total_ratio", "med_risk_score",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "ed_recency", "pcp_disengaged", "complexity_adherence_interaction"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Score all patients in batch. Each gets a raw probability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient in feature_table:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         input_vector = patient[feature_columns]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient.raw_score = model.predict_probability(input_vector)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Also extract feature importance for this specific prediction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // SHAP values tell us WHY this patient scored high or low.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Critical for care managers: "This patient is high-risk because
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // of medication non-adherence and accelerating ED visits."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient.shap_values = model.explain(input_vector)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient.top_risk_drivers = TOP_3_FEATURES_BY_SHAP(patient.shap_values)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN feature_table  // now includes raw_score and risk_drivers per patient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Calibration and stratification.** Raw model scores are recalibrated so that probabilities correspond to actual outcome rates, then patients are assigned to action tiers based on care management capacity. The thresholds are set pragmatically: if your team can manage outreach to 150 patients per week, the "high-risk" tier should capture approximately 150 patients. This is where prediction meets operational reality. Skip calibration and your care managers won't trust the scores. Set thresholds without considering capacity and you'll generate lists that nobody can actually act on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION calibrate_and_stratify(scored_patients, calibration_model, capacity_config):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply Platt scaling (logistic calibration) to raw model outputs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The calibration model was fit on a held-out validation set during training.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient in scored_patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient.calibrated_score = calibration_model.transform(patient.raw_score)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Sort patients by calibrated score, highest risk first.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sorted_patients = SORT scored_patients BY calibrated_score DESCENDING
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Assign tiers based on operational capacity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // These thresholds are tuned to match care management bandwidth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     high_risk_count = capacity_config.weekly_outreach_capacity  // e.g., 150
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     medium_risk_count = high_risk_count * 3  // next 450 for lighter-touch interventions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR i, patient in ENUMERATE(sorted_patients):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF i < high_risk_count:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.risk_tier = "HIGH"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.recommended_action = "Care manager outreach within 48 hours"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF i < high_risk_count + medium_risk_count:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.risk_tier = "MEDIUM"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.recommended_action = "Automated engagement (portal message, text)"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.risk_tier = "LOW"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient.recommended_action = "Standard care, rescore next cycle"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN sorted_patients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Store results and generate outreach lists.** The final step writes calibrated scores to the operational database for real-time lookup and generates the prioritized outreach list that care managers will work from Monday morning. Each record includes not just the score but the top risk drivers (so the care manager knows what to address) and the recommended intervention type. The outreach list is the product of this entire pipeline. If it doesn't reach the right people in a format they can act on, everything upstream was wasted effort.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_and_route(stratified_patients, scoring_date):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write each patient's current risk score to operational database.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This enables real-time lookups from care management tools.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient in stratified_patients:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WRITE to risk_scores_table:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id       = patient.patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             score_date       = scoring_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             risk_score       = patient.calibrated_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             risk_tier        = patient.risk_tier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             top_drivers      = patient.top_risk_drivers  // e.g., ["med_non_adherence", "ed_acceleration"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             recommended_action = patient.recommended_action
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             model_version    = CURRENT_MODEL_VERSION
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             expires_at       = scoring_date + scoring_interval  // score is stale after next cycle
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Generate the outreach list for care management.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Only HIGH and MEDIUM tier patients need active intervention.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     outreach_list = FILTER stratified_patients WHERE risk_tier IN ("HIGH", "MEDIUM")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Group by recommended intervention type for routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     care_manager_list = FILTER outreach_list WHERE risk_tier = "HIGH"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     automated_list    = FILTER outreach_list WHERE risk_tier = "MEDIUM"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Deliver lists to downstream systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     PUBLISH care_manager_list TO care_management_queue
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     PUBLISH automated_list TO patient_engagement_system
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Log pipeline completion for monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     LOG "Scoring complete: {COUNT(stratified_patients)} patients scored, " +
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "{COUNT(care_manager_list)} high-risk, {COUNT(automated_list)} medium-risk"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN scoring_date, COUNT(care_manager_list), COUNT(automated_list)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter07.04-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample output for a high-risk patient:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "patient_id": "PAT-2847291",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "score_date": "2026-06-01",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "risk_score": 0.73,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "risk_tier": "HIGH",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "top_drivers": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"feature": "ed_acceleration", "direction": "increasing", "description": "ED visits accelerating: 4 in last 6mo vs. 5 in prior 12mo"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"feature": "min_pdc", "direction": "decreasing", "description": "Medication adherence dropped to 42% for metformin"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"feature": "pcp_disengaged", "direction": "flag", "description": "No PCP visit in 7 months"}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "recommended_action": "Care manager outreach within 48 hours",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "model_version": "ed-risk-v2.3",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "expires_at": "2026-06-08"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AUROC (discrimination) | 0.72-0.80 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Calibration slope | 0.9-1.1 (well-calibrated) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Positive predictive value (top decile) | 30-45% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Sensitivity (at top 10% threshold) | 25-35% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Batch scoring latency (100K patients) | 8-15 minutes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end pipeline time | 30-60 minutes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per scoring cycle | $10-40 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** Patients new to the system (less than 6 months of history), which limits utilization-based features. Patients whose ED use is driven by factors completely outside the clinical record (domestic violence, acute psychosocial crises). Populations with very low ED base rates where the signal-to-noise ratio is poor. And patients who are genuinely complex and will use the ED regardless of outreach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pseudocode and architecture above demonstrate the pattern. Deploying this to a care management program requires addressing several gaps:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Model validation and fairness testing.** Before deployment, the model needs subgroup analysis: does it perform equally well across race, ethnicity, age, and gender? ED utilization patterns differ systematically across populations, and a model trained on aggregate data can encode those disparities. If your model disproportionately flags Black patients as high-risk (because historical utilization data reflects systemic barriers to primary care access), you need to understand whether that's an accurate signal or an encoded bias, and how your intervention design accounts for it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feedback loop implementation.** The model needs to learn from outcomes. Did the high-risk patients who received outreach actually avoid ED visits? Did the patients scored low-risk end up in the ED anyway? Without this feedback loop, the model degrades over time as the population and care delivery environment change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Intervention capacity alignment.** The model produces as many high-risk patients as you tell it to (via threshold tuning). But care management staffing isn't infinitely elastic. If your team can reach 100 patients per week and the model wants to flag 300, someone needs to make a prioritization decision. Build that constraint into the system design, not as an afterthought.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consent and transparency.** Patients should know they're being proactively monitored. The outreach itself makes this visible ("We noticed you haven't filled your medication recently and wanted to check in"), but organizational policy on predictive analytics disclosure varies. Know your organization's stance before deploying.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's what I've learned from watching ED prediction models in the real world:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The model accuracy ceiling is lower than you expect. Published AUROCs of 0.72-0.80 sound mediocre, and they are, compared to something like fraud detection. But the ceiling is low because a large fraction of ED visits are genuinely unpredictable from historical data. You're not predicting car accidents. You're predicting the subset of ED visits that have precursors visible in claims and pharmacy data. That's a smaller set than "all ED visits."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The hardest problem is not technical. It's operational. I've seen models with perfectly good discrimination sit unused because nobody built the workflow that turns a risk score into a care manager's Monday morning list. The model is 20% of the work. The integration with care management platforms, the outreach protocols, the staffing models, and the outcome tracking are the other 80%.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Feature engineering matters more than algorithm choice. I've watched teams spend months tuning XGBoost hyperparameters for a 0.3% AUC improvement, while ignoring the fact that they hadn't incorporated medication adherence data (which would have given them 3-5% improvement). The features are the model. The algorithm is just the container.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Social determinants are the biggest untapped signal and the hardest to operationalize. ZIP code-level deprivation indices add meaningful lift. But patient-level SDOH data (from screenings, community health worker notes, social service referrals) is transformative when available. The problem is that it's available for maybe 10-20% of patients in most health systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The "preventable" question never goes away. Stakeholders will always ask "what percent of these ED visits were actually preventable?" And the honest answer is "we don't know for certain, because the counterfactual doesn't exist." You can approximate with studies that categorize ED visits by AHRQ criteria (primary-care-sensitive conditions), but there will always be uncertainty about which specific visits the intervention actually prevented.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real-time scoring at care transitions.** Instead of weekly batch scoring only, trigger an immediate rescore when certain high-signal events occur: hospital discharge, ED visit (to catch escalation), medication discontinuation, or missed follow-up appointment. This captures acute risk elevation between batch cycles and enables same-day outreach for patients whose risk just spiked.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-outcome modeling.** Extend beyond binary ED prediction to predict the type of ED visit (primary-care-sensitive vs. mental health crisis vs. injury), which informs different intervention pathways. A patient at risk for a diabetes-related ED visit needs pharmacy outreach. A patient at risk for a mental health crisis needs behavioral health follow-up. Same model infrastructure, different labels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Intervention effectiveness feedback.** Track which interventions actually reduce ED visits for which patient segments. Over time, this builds an evidence base for matching patients to interventions, not just identifying risk. Patients with medication adherence as the top driver respond differently to outreach than patients with transportation as the top driver. Use the feedback data to personalize the intervention, not just the risk score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.1 (Appointment No-Show Prediction):** Shares feature engineering patterns (utilization history, engagement signals) and the same batch scoring architecture at lower stakes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.3 (Patient Churn / Disenrollment Prediction):** Similar behavioral signal detection; patients disengaging from care are at risk for both churn and ED utilization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.5 (30-Day Readmission Risk):** Closely related model architecture; readmission models often share features with ED prediction models and can be trained jointly
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.6 (Rising Risk Identification):** The trajectory version of this problem; identifies patients whose ED risk is accelerating rather than just currently high
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 6.2 (Utilization Pattern Segmentation):** Upstream clustering that can feed into ED prediction as a feature (which utilization segment does this patient belong to?)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
